These observations premised, we maintain that the blood of the embry0, conveyed by the umbilical arteries to the placenta or uterino carunculae, brings not only nutritious juice, but along with this a portion of nitro-adrial particles to the foetus for its support; so that it seems that the blood of the infant is impregnated with nitro-aerial particles by its circula· tion in the umbilical vessels quite in the same way as in the pulmonary vessels. And therefore Ι think that the placenta should no longer be called a uterine liver but rather a uterine lung.
